{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657738"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:33:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:33:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20646"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20646"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.17,0.57,0.09,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13522"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94201"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13522"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20646"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77287"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10955"},{"type":"tags","id":"11585"},{"type":"tags","id":"11780"},{"type":"tags","id":"12534"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32294"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32295"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94201","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94201"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EArachidonic acid is a 20-carbon polyunsaturated fatty acid found in cell membrane phospholipids. When cells are activated by inflammatory stimuli, phospholipase A2 releases arachidonic acid from membrane phospholipids. The free arachidonic acid can then be metabolised via different enzymatic pathways to produce various inflammatory mediators.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the production and function of arachidonic acid metabolites in inflammation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lipoxygenase produces prostaglandins that increase vascular permeability","Cyclooxygenase-2 produces prostaglandins that primarily serve homeostatic functions","Leukotriene B4 promotes neutrophil chemotaxis and activation","Cyclooxygenase-1 produces leukotrienes that cause bronchoconstriction","Lipoxins enhance neutrophil chemotaxis and adhesion to endothelium"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003ELeukotriene B4 promotes neutrophil chemotaxis and activation\u003C/strong\u003E. Leukotrienes are produced from arachidonic acid via the 5-lipoxygenase pathway. LTB4 specifically is a potent chemotactic agent that attracts neutrophils to sites of inflammation and activates them, causing aggregation, adhesion to venular endothelium, generation of reactive oxygen species, and release of lysosomal enzymes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipoxygenase produces prostaglandins that increase vascular permeability\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect because lipoxygenase enzymes produce leukotrienes and lipoxins, not prostaglandins. Prostaglandins are produced via the cyclooxygenase pathway.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECyclooxygenase-2 produces prostaglandins that primarily serve homeostatic functions\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect because COX-2 is mainly induced during inflammation and produces prostaglandins involved in inflammatory responses. It is COX-1 that is constitutively expressed in most tissues and serves various homeostatic functions.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECyclooxygenase-1 produces leukotrienes that cause bronchoconstriction\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect because cyclooxygenase enzymes (COX-1 and COX-2) produce prostaglandins, not leukotrienes. Leukotrienes are produced via the lipoxygenase pathway. While leukotrienes (specifically LTC4, LTD4, and LTE4) do cause bronchoconstriction, they are not produced by COX-1.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipoxins enhance neutrophil chemotaxis and adhesion to endothelium\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect because lipoxins actually suppress inflammation by inhibiting neutrophil chemotaxis and adhesion to endothelium, contrary to what is stated in this option.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArachidonic acid metabolism is a key process in inflammation, with different metabolites serving distinct roles. Prostaglandins (via cyclooxygenase) generally mediate vascular and systemic inflammatory responses, while leukotrienes (via lipoxygenase) are potent mediators of leukocyte recruitment and vascular reactions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Arachidonic acid metabolites are produced from membrane phospholipids and are important mediators of inflammation.","Cyclooxygenase enzymes (COX-1 and COX-2) convert arachidonic acid to prostaglandins, which mediate vascular and systemic inflammatory responses.","Lipoxygenase enzymes convert arachidonic acid to leukotrienes, which are potent mediators of leukocyte recruitment and vascular reactions."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 86-88"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77287"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20646"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77287"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-23T16:07:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-23T16:08:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13522"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94201"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10955"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Acute inflammation","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11585"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Inflammation and repair","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":2,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:14:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11780"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Mediators of inflammation","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-12T14:29:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-12T14:29:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12534","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12534"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Arachidonic acid metabolites","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-23T16:04:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-23T16:04:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/